metadata.title: Beechcraft Super King Air
aws::graph::propositions: Beechcraft Super King Air Model 300 Development and Applications
Model 300LW was developed at the same time as the standard Model 300.
Model 300LW was limited to a maximum takeoff weight (MTOW) of 12,500 lb (5,700 kg).
Model 300LW was developed because not all nations would allow certification of aircraft at an MTOW greater than 12,500 lb (5,700 kg).
Nineteen special versions of the Model 300 were delivered to the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in 1987 and 1988.
The first two Model 300s delivered to the FAA were conversions of standard Model 300s.
The remaining seventeen Model 300s delivered to the FAA were purpose-built.
The FAA has used the fleet of Model 300s to check the extensive network of navigation aids (navaids) in the United States.
200 and 300 Series King Airs have been used for navaid calibration duties in several other countries or regions.
Australia has used 200 and 300 Series King Airs for navaid calibration duties.
Germany has used 200 and 300 Series King Airs for navaid calibration duties.
Hong Kong has used 200 and 300 Series King Airs for navaid calibration duties.
A Beechcraft King Air B200C was used for navaid calibration in Hong Kong.
The Beechcraft King Air B200C was the first aircraft to land at the then-new Chek Lap Kok Airport in 1996.
Norway has used 200 and 300 Series King Airs for navaid calibration duties.
Sweden has used 200 and 300 Series King Airs for navaid calibration duties.
Taiwan has used 200 and 300 Series King Airs for navaid calibration duties.

text: Because not all nations would then allow an aircraft of this type to be certified at an MTOW greater than 12,500 lb (5,700 kg), the Model 300LW was also developed at the same time, limited to the lower MTOW. Nineteen examples of a special version of the Model 300 were delivered to the FAA in 1987 and 1988. The first two were conversions of standard Model 300s, while the remaining 17 were purpose-built; since they were delivered the FAA has used the fleet to check the extensive network of navaids in the United States. 200 and 300 Series King Airs have been used for similar duties in several other countries or regions, including Australia, Germany, Hong Kong (a B200C used for navaid calibration was the first aircraft to land at the then-new Chek Lap Kok Airport in 1996), Norway, Sweden and Taiwan.
